Exploring and Communicating Data Findings of FordGoBike Data, San Francisco, To Identify Growth Opportunies Among User Segments¶

by (Doaa Salahedin Ahmed)¶

02/2021

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The Ford Go Bike is the Bike-share system operating in SanFrancisco Bay Area, USA. Present at more than 360 stations across San Francisco with two types of plans:

  • Subscriber: a monthly or annual Membership that grants the member unlimited 45-minute trips.
  • Customer: a single ride access that grants the casual user a 30-minute ride within 24 hours.

Our dataset belongs to february 2019 and includes users data, stations, and time/date of servicing for each trip. At the time of this project, it was not to download historic data from the provided hyperlinks. Therefore the investigated data can be summerized as follows:

  • Trip_duration (in seconds)
  • Trip start time and date
  • Trip end time and date
  • Start station name
  • Start station id
  • start station coordinate (latitude and longitude)
  • End station name
  • End station id
  • End station coordinate (latitude and longitude)
  • Bike id
  • User type
  • User birth year
  • User gender Source of data: https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2020/October/5f91cf38_201902-fordgobike-tripdata/201902-fordgobike-tripdata.csv

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • Our dataset has 183,412 rows and 16 columns in total.
  • Each row (observation) represents a bike trip that started during February 2019 in Sanfrancisco.

Types of data:

  • Categorical: stations' names, user type (subscriber/casual user), gender, and bike Id.
  • Numerical: trips' durations, the coordinates of the stations (latitude/longitude), and births years.
  • Some users didn't provid their year of birth or their gender during the registration process. All of these fragmentations need to be taken into account, during the exploration phase.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I am interested in the usage patterns, such as trip duration and the number of trips.
  • We will further explore the optimum users demographic criteria for Ford-GoBike services.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Trips frequencies, trip duration, and the criteria of the users segmentation.

# We will set this function to detect the outliers, in our case I'm interested in the upperbound only:

def detect_outlier(data):
    # find q1 and q3 values
    q1, q3 = np.percentile(sorted(data), [25, 75])
 
    # compute IRQ
    iqr = q3 - q1
 
    # find lower and upper bounds
    upper_bound = q3 + (1.5 * iqr)
#    lower_bound = q1 - (1.5 * iqr) - x <= lower_bound or
    
    Outliers = [x for x in data if x >= upper_bound]
    
    return Outliers

From the first 2 heatmaps we can observe that the usage patterns (number of rides and duration) vary proportionally in a positive direction within the same user segment, for instance, users segments with higher numbers of rides are also recording higher dusrations, and this is quite logic and supported by the matched colorization hues for each segment in the 2 heatmaps.

On the other side, the dark cooler colorizations on the first 2 heatmaps can be an indicator for untapped opportunities or otherwise non-existing need. Knowing that the female population of San Francisco are quit high, we shall advise on expanding the marketing activities and allocating more budget to penetrate this segment.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Through this part, we have uncovered our segmented audeinces usage pattrens, in terms of time, trip duration, frequencies, and purpose.

It is now more evident that the most common trips hours are early in the morning between 8.00 AM and 10.00 AM, and in the evening from 4.00PM and 6.00PM, we can say these are our daily rush hours except for Satudays and Sundays where these peaks disappear.

Additionally, we could rationalize the difference in the trip duration between the subscribers and the customers types, that the subscribers are regular users who can manage the trip time more efficiently.

We can see also that young adult male subscribers aged between 25 to 34 years old recorded the highest usage rates and they generally take less than 9 minutes per ride on average. We can say that this segment, followed by the male older subsegment, are the main users for the Ford-GoBike Service as indicated by the hot colorizations in first 2 heatmaps. Therefore, we can advise Ford-Gobike to sustain marketing activities for this segment as it showed the extreme need for the service and it would be useful to keep these users' loyalty.

We would also recommend extra marketing research on the female subjects could an outstanding opportunity for expansion.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Sure there are many interesting findings to highligh, for instance, we could see from the third heatmap that female subscribers and female customers consume a bit longer duration per trip than male users, we can also see that the older the user, the longer duration the ride takes.

We can also confirm the fact that customers from both genders tend to consume nearly 1.5X - 2X the duration taken by subscribers.
